Class Constructors

Constructors are special methods that run when a new instance is created with the `new` keyword.

### Basic Constructor

```typescript
class User {
  name: string;
  email: string;

  constructor(name: string, email: string) {
    this.name = name;
    this.email = email;
  }
}
```

### Parameter Properties

Shorthand syntax that declares and initializes properties:

```typescript
class User {
  constructor(
    public name: string,
    public email: string,
    private age?: number
  ) {}
  // The properties: name, email, age are auto-created
}
```

### Overload Constructors

TypeScript supports constructor overloads:

```typescript
class Point {
  x: number;
  y: number;

  constructor();
  constructor(x: number, y: number);
  constructor(x?: number, y?: number) {
    this.x = x ?? 0;
    this.y = y ?? 0;
  }
}

const origin = new Point();
const point = new Point(3, 4);
```

### Default Values in Constructors

```typescript
class Config {
  constructor(
    public host: string = "localhost",
    public port: number = 3000
  ) {}
}

const c1 = new Config();
const c2 = new Config("example.com", 443);
```

### Calling Super in Derived Classes

```typescript
class Animal {
  constructor(public name: string) {}
}

class Dog extends Animal {
  constructor(name: string, public breed: string) {
    super(name); // Must call super before using 'this'
  }
}
```

> **Key Point:** Parameter properties with access modifiers are the most concise way to define class properties.

codeExample:
class HttpRequest {
  constructor(
    public method: "GET" | "POST" | "PUT" | "DELETE",
    public url: string,
    public headers: Record<string, string> = {},
    private body?: unknown
  ) {}

  send(): Promise<Response> {
    return fetch(this.url, {
      method: this.method,
      headers: this.headers,
      body: JSON.stringify(this.body)
    });
  }
}

const req = new HttpRequest("GET", "/api/users");
